<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many months should I plan a wedding in?", answer: "12–14 months is the most common engagement-to-wedding timeline in the US, according to The Knot's annual surveys. Smaller weddings (under 50 guests) can be planned in 4–6 months. Larger weddings (over 150 guests) often take 14–18 months to coordinate all the vendors. Destination weddings need an extra 4–6 months for guest travel planning. Whatever your size, more time gives you better vendor selection and more competitive pricing." },
  { question: "What should I do 12 months before the wedding?", answer: "Set the budget, draft a guest list, choose 3–5 venues to visit, book the venue (this is the single most important booking — venue availability drives everything else), book the photographer and DJ/band (the next most-booked vendors), and start dress shopping. Custom dresses take 6–8 months to make and 2 months to alter, so you need to order around the 9-month mark to be safe." },
  { question: "What should I do the month of the wedding?", answer: "Confirm final headcount with caterer (usually 2 weeks before), confirm timeline with all vendors, do final dress fitting, pick up rings, write speeches and vows, prepare wedding party gifts, pack for the honeymoon, and plan the day-after brunch. The last week is for confirming, not deciding — every major decision should be locked by the 2-week mark." },
  { question: "Is 6 months enough time to plan a wedding?", answer: "Yes — for small to medium weddings (under 100 guests), 6 months is doable. The biggest constraints are venue and vendor availability, especially during peak season (May–October). Off-season weddings (Jan–Apr, Nov–Dec) are easier to plan in 6 months because most vendors have open dates. Larger weddings or peak-season Saturdays really do need 12+ months to avoid scrambling." },
  { question: "What's the best season to get married?", answer: "October is the most popular month in the US (cool weather, pretty foliage, peak photographer demand). May, June, and September are also peak. The off-season — January through March, plus November-December — offers 20–40% discounts on venues and vendors but limits outdoor options. Saturday is the most popular day; Friday and Sunday weddings usually save 20–30% on venue cost." }
]) %>

